                Late-Onset Alzheimer's Disease (LOAD)—representing the most prevalent form, typically manifesting clinically after the age of 65—is understood to emerge not from a singular, identifiable cause, but rather from a highly complex, lifelong interplay. Involving factors that cannot be altered (non-modifiable risks) and those related to lifestyle choices, environmental exposures, and overall health status that can potentially be influenced (modifiable risks), interplay occurs throughout life. Accumulating and interacting dynamically across an individual's entire lifespan, diverse factors contribute.
